3.1.1 Semi-Structured Interviewa

Semi-structured interviews were conducted to get descriptive information for qualitative analysis. Additionally, they provide an agenda for the interview while still allowing the interviewer to further inquire about interesting answers provided by the interviewee as the interview unfolds. In this waya, the data collected is highly relevant and ensures that the interview does not miss useful aspects. The questions in the script combines Kvales [Kvale] two metaphors of using an interview as a miner and a traveller. The miner metaphor involves asking specific questions on hard facts. On the contrary, the traveller metaphor attempts to construct knowledge between the interviewer and the interviewee by asking opena-ended questions. The traveller metaphor is important because it helps us understand how the family interactas and is one of the key reasons for conducting interviews compared to a questionnaire. a

A similar method is direct observation that also takes place in controlled environments. However, since we are interested in the group as a whole and not the in, ,[,Y,v,o,n,n,e, ,R,o,g,e,r,]dividual participant we settled for observation.The style of observation is similar to direct observation in controlled environments, since the participants are in a con,strolled environment, however the observation is not only focused on the individual, as it is in directed observation, but also how the group interact with the prototypes. These observations combined with the final interview resulted in a mix of quantitative and qualitative information. ,

Observation provides knowledge about how people actually interact with prototypes, aside from questionnaires and interview. There can be a difference between what participants sa and what participants actually do [Yvonne Roger]. When interview sing, the participants can feel it necessary to say, what they believe is the correct answer instead of what the participant really thinks. To limit this bias observation can help discover what the participant actually do and see if it is consistent with what the participant say.3.1.4 DIndirect Observation
